Narrator

Your parents named you Anton. As the only child of a diligent civil servant, you lived quite an ordinary childhood.

Life was not bad. You were lucky enough to attend a well-known public school.

But frequent fights broke out at the Rayne family home, which made you feel uneasy.

Narrator

Your parents named you Anton. As the only child of a farmer, you spent your childhood among wheat fields.

Life was not easy. You were too poor to afford a good education.

The Rayne family was caring regardless of the economically dire situation. Your parents always did their best to support you.

Narrator

During a history class at school, the bell started to ring unexpectedly. You heard a loud commotion outside.\n\nAs everyone tried to figure out what was going on, the principal announced the historic revolution. \n\nThe Kingdom was no more. The Republic of Sordland was born.

1923|September 9th

PlaySoundEffect(School); WaitForMessage(Continue);

Player

You did not fully understand.

Player

You were happy that you had the day off.

Narrator

After graduating, you passed the university exam with high marks.\n\nYou had the opportunity to choose between several studies. You chose...

1926

Player

...History at the Deyr University of Culture.

Narrator

During the first year you attended a lecture with Deivid Wisci. He was a well-known diplomat from the Foreign Ministry and the son of the President.

After observing the hall in silence, he explained how the Supreme Court is obstructing justice in Sordland. 

He stated that laws should be applied fairly, and that even the members of the Supreme Court, are subject to the same laws.

Narrator

During the first year you attended a lecture with Deivid Wisci. He was a well-known diplomat from the Foreign Ministry and the son of the President.

After observing the hall in silence, he explained why Realpolitik is important for a successful foreign policy.

He argued that a strategy based on practical and material factors would be much more successful in reaching Sordland's ambitions.

Narrator

Soldiers entered the campus in the evening ahead of the first election.\n\nMany were in shock as the uniformed men created a security cordon and started arresting the teachers. \n\nA group of students started gathering in protest. Along with your best friend Petr Vectern, you decided to...

1927|May 22nd

Narrator

The majority of the students and teachers displayed their opposition.\n\nThus, Lachaven became a target for the military regime.\n\nYou didn't want to stay idle and decided to join...

1927|October 10th

Narrator

The coup split the students into two groups and caused frequent fights. \n\nTorture and imprisonment of any opposing voice became a daily routine in Deyr.\n\nYou didn't want to stay idle and decided to join...

1927|October 10th

Narrator

A student fell and was trampled as everybody started running away.

Player

You tried to go out to see.

Narrator

Unlike the others, you were lucky to escape.

Player

You tried to bury yourself under the sheets.

Narrator

But the soldiers locked the doors.

Narrator

The dozens of debates helped you hone your oratory skills while also helping you grow your network.

Even though the discussions between different groups often became heated, you all grew from sharing ideas.

In one of the meetings, Petr Vectern introduced you to a classmate of his, Monica. You were immediately attracted to...

Narrator

The politically charged environment led you to...

Player

...join the Red Youth, the socialists.

Player

Narrator

The radio relayed that the communist general Rikard surrounded Luderin and his troops, demanding their surrender.\n\nThey refused and heavy fighting broke out across the country. \n\nYou just couldn't believe it. The army was fighting amongst themselves.

1928|June 2nd

PlaySoundEffect(Newscaster); WaitForMessage(Continue);

Narrator

Rikard's sudden attack caused even more bloodshed in the country. 

He seemed different compared to fascist Luderin. In your opinion however, he was more of the same. 

So you participated in a protest march. You were chanting...

Player

...“United we stand, divided we fall!”

Player

You ran to save her.

Narrator

The clashes escalated into a full blown civil war. The horrors made you isolate yourself for a while.

Monica helped you cope and love grew between the two of you.

However, it was a difficult time for love.

Narrator

The charismatic Colonel, Tarquin Soll, orchestrated a sudden attack on the capital where the Luderinist and Rikardist forces were battling each other. He defeated both, ending the war.\n\nA new constitution was written, and the military government began efforts to restore stability. Many people saw the Colonel as a savior. \n\nHe formed the United Sordland party and ran as a presidential candidate. In the first-ever single-party elections...

1929|Republic of Sordland

Narrator

A devastating civil war broke out in the neighboring country, Wehlen. It quickly turned into a proxy war between regional and world powers.\n\nThe distinguished major, Iosef Lancea, ordered you to lead your squad on a border patrol mission.\n\nIt was a very cold winter night when you began marching out of Gumren Outpost.

1930|February|Bergia Region

Player

Your only concern was passing the exams.

Player

You could see your breath.

Narrator

You became the legal assistant to one of the more experienced members of assembly.\n\nYou worked long and hard, going through hundreds of pages of legal documents late into the night.

Narrator

You became the economics assistant to one of the more experienced members of assembly.\n\nYou worked long and hard, investigating hundreds of pages of economic reports late into the night.

Narrator

You became the foreign policy assistant to one of the more experienced members of assembly.\n\nYou worked long and hard, reviewing dozens of foreign policy plans late into the night.

Player

It was the best opportunity to change the country for the better.

Player

You were climbing the ladder.

Narrator

President Soll barely secured a majority in the election against the opposition leader.\n\nOver the next year, the Sordish people grew increasingly discontent with corruption and the worsening quality of life. Economic growth was slowing down.\n\nMeanwhile, calls for a United Sordland Party congress became louder as a leadership struggle started to brew. You...

1945|October|Time of Change

Narrator

The president offered you the position of Minister of Economy, Commerce and Energy in the next government if you backed him in the upcoming vote.

Narrator

The president offered you the position of Minister of Foreign Affairs and Trade in the next government if you backed him in the upcoming vote.

Narrator

The congress was nothing short of impressive. The banners of the United Sordland Party were decorating every possible spot.\n\nThousands of influential political figures, lobbyists and benefactors gathered for this turning point. \n\nThe voting for the party leadership began.

1946|August

PlaySoundEffect(Congress); WaitForMessage(Continue);

Player

You voted for Ewald Alphonso.

Player

You voted for Tarquin Soll.

Player

...didn't care about who was in charge.

Narrator

The Presidency of Alphonso saw many bold reforms in government and law and advancements in liberal democratic values.\n\nHowever, due to infighting and disorganization, continental economic tensions, and fast-track privatization, it was followed by a severe economic recession.\n\nThe other parties announced their bids for the 1953 election, but the unfair election system hampered opposition efforts to campaign. You...

1951|Summer|A New Sordland

Narrator

He listened to your advice. \n\nAlphonso conceded the leadership struggle and the party eventually voted you in because of your indisputable influence.\n\nFollowing this, you announced that you would be running for President in the general election with Petr as your running mate.

1953|March

Player

...worried that your reputation would be tarnished along with Alphonso.

Player

You never forgot her face.

Player

The chaos had to end.

Narrator

A month later, your daughter was born. Monica named her Deana. She motivated you during a tumultuous period in the party.\n\nAs the VP and the leader of the USP, Ewald Alphonso began dismantling the old organizations and structures established by the USP such as the State Educators Corps and the Sordish State Corporation Bills.\n\nThe general elections were approaching. The United Sordland party was under new leadership. You...

1946|October 15th|Uncertain Years

Player

...did your best not to help him.

Player

...dedicated yourself to the party and its success.

Narrator

After visiting every city and town during the campaign, you made a speech on state television.\n\nYou promised to...

Player

Player

Narrator

The contender for party leadership was Ewald Alphonso, a reformist and talented business magnate with a growing follower base within the party.\n\nMeanwhile, in a desperate effort to secure votes before the congress, President Soll was meeting party members one by one.

1946|July

Narrator

Unfortunately, Tarquin Soll lost the leadership vote to Ewald Alphonso by a small margin. \n\nDuring the congress, Soll announced he would retire from politics at the end of his term, and appointed Alphonso as Vice President.\n\nThe systems he had established were to stay much longer; his achievements wouldn't be forgotten. You...

...were troubled by the departure of Soll.

Player

Player

Player

Player

After the patrol, Major Lancea arrived with anger and immediately relieved you of your command, calling you a disappointment.

One of your squad members had reported your actions.

After several months of scrubbing the floors as a punishment...

Narrator

The media backlash prompted President Alphonso to reshuffle his cabinet, but most of his inner circle, even Minister of Development Gus Manger, abandoned him.\n\nAlphonso was removed from power by a no-confidence vote. The party eventually voted you in because of your influence.\n\nFollowing this, you announced that you would be running for President in the general election with Petr as your running mate.

1953|March

Player

...your duties ended and you went back to civilian life.

Narrator

During your absence, Petr Vectern found trustworthy contacts and strengthened your position in the party.\n\nAt the same time, President Soll increased his authority over the years. His growing ego started to cause strife within the USP.

1941|October

Player

Player

Narrator

Just like your father once did, you prioritized work over family. Along with Petr Vectern, you accomplished great things for your party. \n\nAt home, Monica and Franc felt your absence.\n\nMeanwhile, President Soll increased his authority over the years.
